<div id="review_3364354234" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3364354234" />
    <a title="Tamara" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5647161-tamara"><img alt="Tamara" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1308282952p2/5647161.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3364354234?book_show_action=true">Jun 21, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tamara" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tamara" href="/user/show/5647161-tamara">Tamara</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/33667229-the-aureate-spectacles">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3364354234" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7179759122008897787">Been holding off on this review for a while because I wanted to digest my thoughts a bit and figure out a not-mean way to say that the writing style was killing me, but now my brain is trying to erase this book from itself so I gotta do it now. Gave it two stars because the story was interesting enough that I managed to skim through the rest of the book once I hit my breaking point. I suppose a big hint as to what I got myself into should have been the absolutely incomprehensible first sentence.</span>
  <span id="freeText7179759122008897787" style="display:none">Been holding off on this review for a while because I wanted to digest my thoughts a bit and figure out a not-mean way to say that the writing style was killing me, but now my brain is trying to erase this book from itself so I gotta do it now. Gave it two stars because the story was interesting enough that I managed to skim through the rest of the book once I hit my breaking point. I suppose a big hint as to what I got myself into should have been the absolutely incomprehensible first sentence. It really felt like the author was 20k under the word count and instead of fleshing out the story, she just added a ton of adjectives and rambling monologues. I'm still not over 'Michaela's negotiating knees' and 'a look of testosterous satisfaction.'<br /><br />I don't want this review to turn into a rant, but I gotta ask one question to the void:<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ wtf was up with the aunt? She was genuinely distressing. It really did seem like she was being purposefully abusive with the ostentatious glasses and then it all devolved into straight up illegal abuse. She could have just given Michaela a normal pair of glasses from the beginning - a point that is proven when she <i>gives her a normal pair of glasses</i>. Of course, this is only after Michaela breaks free of a muzzle contraption the aunt strapped to her face by tying her to a bed and like, stepping on her face with a high heel to wrench the muzzle as tight as possible. If you could have given her a normal pair of glasses this whole time, <i>you were just psychologically torturing a child!</i> <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span></span>
  <a data-text-id="7179759122008897787" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


